🟦 Slide 2 – Background
Introduction
Breast cancer is one of the leading causes of cancer-related deaths among women worldwide.

Early detection significantly increases survival rate.

Traditional diagnosis depends on biopsy and medical imaging.

Machine Learning enables automated prediction using clinical data.

🟦 Slide 3 – Problem Statement
Problem Statement
Although many studies apply machine learning to breast cancer detection:

Different studies use different experimental setups

Many focus only on accuracy

Lack of standardized comparison under identical conditions

Limited discussion on confusion matrix metrics

Therefore, a comprehensive comparative framework is required.

🟦 Slide 4 – Research Objectives
Objectives of the Study
Compare multiple ML algorithms on the same dataset

Use standardized preprocessing and evaluation

Evaluate using multiple performance metrics

Identify the most reliable classifier

🟦 Slide 5 – Literature Review
Related Research
Recent studies (2021–2025) have:

Used Wisconsin Breast Cancer Dataset

Applied Logistic Regression, KNN, Decision Tree

Achieved accuracy between 92%–99%

Identified Logistic Regression or SVM as top performers

However:

Most studies do not compare all major classifiers together.

🟦 Slide 6 – Research Gap
Identified Research Gap
No unified evaluation framework

Limited multi-metric comparison

Inconsistent preprocessing techniques

Lack of statistical validation

This study addresses these limitations.

